s out in paperback, and we at Guardian Children’s books want to take another look. We’re going to take a leaf out of site member <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2015/jan/31/art-of-being-normal-lisa-williamson-review\">emybot’s</a> book: ‘This is a book that has to be read and has to be talked about’. Well, reading and talking is what we’re all about.</p> <h2>The Art of Being Normal</h2> <p>Two boys. Two secrets. David Piper has always been an outsider. His parents think he’s gay. The school bully thinks he’s a freak. Only his two best friends know the real truth - David wants to be a girl. On the first day at his new school Leo Denton has one goal - to be invisible. Attracting the attention of the most beautiful girl in year 11 is definitely not part of that plan. When Leo stands up for David in a fight, an unlikely friendship forms. But things are about to get messy. Because at Eden Park School secrets have a funny habit of not staying secret for long ... </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/bad3971842d5700c5ed088b492fa5828004cb445/0_0_257_400/257.jpg\" alt=\"fdf\" width=\"257\" height=\"400\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <h2>Read an extract here and then claim your copy!</h2> <h2>How to enter<br /></h2> <p>Ten teen readers, a copy of this gripping story of friendship and self-discovery (plus a tote bag) could be yours! Just enter this prize draw by <strong>emailing childrens.books@theguardian.com</strong> with the following details: your name, your age, your address, your parent or guardian’s name, your parent or guardian’s telephone number.</p> <p>Entrants must be between 13 and 18 years of age. After the draw closes at <strong>midnight on Tuesday 12 January 2016</strong> we will pick 10 winners at random, who will each receive a copy of Th