","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/world/world","sectionName":"World news","references":[]},{"id":"education/languages","webTitle":"Languages","type":"keyword","sectionId":"education","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/education/languages","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/education/languages","sectionName":"Education","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/news","webTitle":"News","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/news","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/news","references":[]},{"id":"profile/davidbarnett","webTitle":"David Barnett","r2ContributorId":"26173","firstName":"david","lastName":"barnett","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>David Barnett is a journalist in the north of England and the author of two novels, Hinterland and Angelglass</p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/davidbarnett","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/davidbarnett","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-01-06T07:38:24Z","webTitle":"A fish called Tim Winton: scientists name new species after novelist","sectionId":"environment","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"environment/2016/jan/06/fish-called-tim-winton-scientists-name-new-species-after-australia-novelist","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Monica Tan","headline":"A fish called Tim Winton: scientists name new species after novelist","trailText":"The ‘very beautiful’ gold and silver coloured grunter is one of 20 newly-identified fish species from the remote Kimberley in Western Australia ","hasStoryPackage":"false","productionOffice":"AUS","body":"<p>Tim Winton – best-selling Australian writer and now, also, a fish species newly identified by a team of bioscientists. The 30cm-long grunter was one of 20 new fish species recorded during fieldwork in the Kimberley, in northern Western Australian.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"12dbe591ae1e0def1f84acfb53abade5a6b52b11\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/12dbe591ae1e0def1f84acfb53abade5a6b52b11/1193_196_1905_2858/667.jpg\" alt=\"Western Australian writer and conservationist Tim Winton in 2013.\" width=\"667\" height=\"1000\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Western Australian writer and conservationist Tim Winton in 2013.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: Penguin/Jono Van Hest</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Team leader Dr Tim Dempster from the University of Melbourne said there were roughly 200 known species of freshwater fish in Australia and these 20 additional species represented a 10% increase. “If we can double the number of known fish species unique to the Kimberley in just three years, it can only mean the entire biodiversity of life in Kimberley rivers is underestimated.”</p> <p>The species were identified during nine months of fieldwork across 17 Kimberley rivers between 2012 and 2014. Twelve of the 20 species were discovered within a three-week period in 2013 by researchers James Shelley and Matthew Le Feuvre when they accessed some of Australia’s most remote rivers by helicopter. </p> <p>Tim Winton was one of two species discovered within five minutes of reaching the Prince Regent River by helicopter. Le Feuvre said: “We could see from the surface of the river there were at least two new species that weren’t in the field guide. That’s how different they were. You don’t need to get them in your hand, they just jump out at you.”</p> <p>The fish is endemic to the area, and is golden coloured on the top and silver on the bottom. “It’s a very beautiful looking fish with a very classic fish shape,” Le Feuvre said. </p> <p>They thought it would be a “good gesture” to name the fish after the writer. “He’s been a champion of conservation in the Kimberley and aquatic environments,” Le Feuvre said. “And he’s a very famous Western Australian as well.”</p> <p>Winton called the naming a “great honour” in <a href=\"http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2015/s4382050.htm\">an interview with the ABC</a>. “When I first heard about this little fish, you know, the greenie in me thought, ‘Well, I wonder what kind of fish it is and I wonder what its habits are and what its habitat is.’ Then the redneck in me thought, ‘Well, I wonder what it tastes like?’”</p> <p>The new species fall within three categories: 16 Terapontidae (grunters), three Eleotridae (gudgeons) and one Atherinidae (hardy heads). </p> <p>The others have not yet been named, but Le Feuvre said they would be given Latin scientific names and the scientists were also working with local Indigenous communities – for whom the fish were once or continued to be important food sources – to find appropriate common names.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--supporting\" data-media-id=\"0cca961b11c83ea0ef85c0515ea26f863f4257a7\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/0cca961b11c83ea0ef85c0515ea26f863f4257a7/0_106_1599_960/1000.jpg\" alt=\"Matthew Le Feuvre in the Kimberley.\" width=\"1000\" height=\"600\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\">Matthew Le Feuvre in the Kimberley.</span> <span class=\"element-image__credit\">Photograph: James Shelley/Matthew Le Feuvre</span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>The Kimberley is among the least researched areas of Australia, due to its remoteness. Le Feuvre said the fish discovered were likely to just be the “tip of the iceberg”. “If you begin to look at amphibians and invertebrates – who knows what the actual diversity of northern Australia aquatic ecosystems actually is.”</p> <p> No fish species in the Kimberley, one of Australia’s most pristine regions, were listed for conservation, partly due to the lack of scientific knowledge around the area. “You can’t conserve what you don’t know exists,” Le Feuvre said.</p> <p>He said conservation listing tended to be “reactive, rather than proactive” and added, “there is an opportunity for proactive conservation in the Kimberley and get really good management plans in place before development begins”. Threats to the Kimberley include large-scale agriculture, mining and climate change.</p>","liveBloggingNow":"false","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4fhcm","wordcount":"558","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5/112_0_1284_771/140.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-01-09T07:45:00Z","standfirst":"<p>The ‘very beautiful’ gold and silver coloured grunter is one of 20 newly-identified fish species from the remote Kimberley in Western Australia </p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/jan/06/fish-called-tim-winton-scientists-name-new-species-after-australia-novelist","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/environment/2016/jan/06/fish-called-tim-winton-scientists-name-new-species-after-australia-novelist","sectionName":"Environment","elements":[{"id":"e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5/112_0_1284_771/1000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5","altText":"Tim Winton, a newly identified fish species named after the best-selling Western Australian writer. ","caption":"Tim Winton, a newly identified fish species named after the best-selling Western Australian writer. ","source":"James Shelley/Matthew Le Feuvre","credit":"Photograph: James Shelley/Matthew Le Feuvre","mediaId":"e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5","displayCredit":"true","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/e4a52169a0dea23cee0fe51e574d5f18af72d3d5/112_0_1284_771/1000.jpg","width":"1000","height":"600"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://medi